XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY: This crash occurred on a two lane undivided roadway, slightly curving to the right prior to the crash site, with no grade and a posted speed limit of 89 KMPH (55MPH). the weather was clear and the roadway was dry. This crash occurred on a weekday afternoon. Vehicle #2, a 1990 Ford Mustang, was traveling south on the two lane undivided roadway when it proceeded to pass a box truck (as per the driver of vehicle #1). It impacted with Vehicle #1 a 2000 Pontiac Grand Am, head on in the northbound lane. Vehicle #2 came to rest on the east shoulder facing south. Vehicle #1 came to rest on the east shoulder facing north. The Critical Precrash Event coded to Vehicle #2 was This Vehicle Traveling Over the Lane line on Left Side of Travel Lane. The Critical Reason for the Critical Precrash Event was coded as Driver Related Factor, Inadequate Surveillance (e.g. failed to look, looked but did not see.) There is no evidence of any illegal drug use, however the Police Report for this crash could not be obtained. The Ford Mustang (Vehicle #2) was driven by a 20 year old male who was flown to an area trauma center with head neck and back injuries. No interview was obtained as researcher was unable to locate or contact this driver. The driver of the Pontiac Grand Am (Vehicle #1) was a 49 year old belted male who was flown to an area trauma center. This driver stated that Vehicle #1 came from behind a box truck into his lane. It should be noted here that the driver of this vehicle stated he has a heart condition for which he takes prescription medications. Both vehicles were towed from the scene. The Critical Precrash Event coded to Vehicle #1 was Other Motor Vehicle in Lane. No Critical Reason for Critical Precrash Event was coded to this vehicle.
